  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the difference between enum, union and struct in C programming?",
  "response": "Let me explain the differences between enum, union, and struct in C programming:\n\n1. Enum (Enumeration):\n```c\nenum Color {\n    RED,    // 0\n    GREEN,  // 1\n    BLUE    // 2\n};\n\n// Characteristics:\n// - Defines a set of named integer constants\n// - By default, first value is 0, subsequent incremented\n// - Can specify custom integer values\nenum Color {\n    RED = 5,\n    GREEN = 10,\n    BLUE = 15\n};\n```\n\n2. Struct:\n```c\nstruct Person {\n    char name[50];\n    int age;\n    float height;\n};\n\n// Characteristics:\n// - Can store multiple different data types\n// - Each member has its own memory space\n// - Total memory is sum of all member sizes\nstruct Person p1;\np1.age = 30;\n```\n\n3. Union:\n```c\nunion Data {\n    int i;\n    float f;\n    char str[20];\n};\n\n// Characteristics:\n// - All members share same memory location\n// - Size is equal to largest member\n// - Only one member can be used at a time\nunion Data data;\ndata.i = 10;    // Now using integer memory\ndata.f = 220.5; // Overwrites previous value\n```\n\nKey Differences:\n\nEnum:\n- Creates named integer constants\n- Used for defining a set of related constants\n- Typically used for improved code readability\n- Smallest memory footprint\n\nStruct:\n- Groups different data types together\n- Each member has its own memory space\n- Total memory is sum of all members\n- Used to create complex data structures\n- Can represent a record with multiple attributes\n\nUnion:\n- Allows storing different data types in same memory location\n- Only one member can be active at a time\n- Size is equal to largest member\n- Useful for memory-efficient type punning\n- Requires careful management to avoid data corruption\n\nExample to illustrate differences:\n```c\n// Enum usage\nenum Days { \n    MONDAY, \n    TUESDAY, \n    WEDNESDAY \n};\n\n// Struct usage\nstruct Employee {\n    int id;\n    char name[50];\n    float salary;\n};\n\n// Union usage\nunion Converter {\n    int i;\n    float f;\n    char c;\n};\n\nint main() {\n    // Enum\n    enum Days today = WEDNESDAY;\n\n    // Struct\n    struct Employee emp;\n    emp.id = 101;\n    strcpy(emp.name, \"John\");\n    emp.salary = 5000.50;\n\n    // Union\n    union Converter data;\n    data.i = 10;      // Using integer\n    data.f = 220.5;   // Now using float (overwrites previous value)\n\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nMemory Comparison:\n```c\n// Assuming 32-bit system\nsizeof(enum Days)        // Typically 4 bytes\nsizeof(struct Employee)  // 4 + 50 + 4 = 58 bytes\nsizeof(union Converter)  // 4 bytes (size of largest member)\n```\n\nUse Cases:\n- Enum: State machines, switch statements, constants\n- Struct: Complex data structures, records\n- Union: Type conversion, memory-efficient storage, low-level programming\n\nChoose based on your specific programming requirements and memory constraints.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
